With approximately 4750 species grouped in 26 families, parasitic plants account for 1,6% of all angiosperms (

). Parasitic plants are components of almost all terrestrial vegetation 
types
(

). In plants, the parasitic lifestyle is characterized by developing an intrusive organ called a haustorium, a vascular bridge that connects the two plants that also acts on attachment and host tissue penetration (

) and absorbs water and nutrients from host-plant vascular tissue. Holoparasites (no photosynthesis and chlorophyll absent) have lower transpiration rates than hemiparasites (photoautotrophic and chlorophyll present) because holoparasites are underground for most of their lifecycle; even after emergence, they do not photosynthesize due to the lack of leaves necessary for effective transpiration (

; 

). Holoparasites infect both the phloem and xylem of the host tissue and rely on the host to supply both organic and inorganic nutrients (

). Haustorium cells metabolize host-derived nutrients, creating a parasite-specific metabolic profile (

; 

; P´eron et al., 2016), which may be completely different in holoparasites

when compared to hosts, particularly regarding polyphenols (

, 

).

Parasitism represents the most extreme interaction between plants, and plant parasitism offers a unique opportunity to study correlational nutritional relationships (

). Interestingly, parasites generally accumulate more inorganic and organic compounds than their hosts, which has a notable effect on subsequent processes and associated mechanisms (

; 

; 

). Therefore, holoparasites lower their water potentials by accumulating high levels of osmotically active compounds such as mineral ions, sugars, and sugar alcohols (

). The gradient of the water potential between the host and the parasite is a driving force for water flow (

). However, many questions remain about this process, especially regarding which 
types
of materials are translocated from host to parasite, whether the parasite is selective in extracting certain compounds and excluding others, and how the parasite uses the acquired material, including toxic compounds (

). An interesting and poorly understood phenomenon is the relation between the parasitic lifestyle in plants and resistance against toxic trace elements in polluted soils. Parasites can reduce the concentration of heavy metals in the host due to their high accumulation tendencies. However, identifying the mechanism by which this occurs and determining whether compounds withdrawn from the host are already chelated to reduce toxicity prior to parasite uptake, whether the parasite has specific chelating mechanisms, or whether parasitic plants may play a role in bioremediation in removing metals, salt, or other soil contaminants are still required (

; 

; 

; 

; 

).

Parasites can be considered keystone species because they influence the individual growth, reproduction, and allometry of other species, as well as ecosystems and ecological communities through their effects on trophic interactions in abiotic compounds and other organisms (

). It is also interesting that hyperparasitic interactions between parasitic plants may affect not only the ecology of individual species or nutrient sharing but also modulate their ecosystem impacts (

). Some parasites are allogenic engineers that change the environment by transforming materials from one physical state to another, particularly in nutrient-poor communities, from less available forms into more labile forms (

). Parasitic plants also tend to have much higher nutrient concentrations than their hosts (

), usually several times the N and P in the leaves of root hemiparasites (

, 

, 

; 

). Thus, they have considerable impacts on local biogeochemical cycling due to their enriched and easily decomposed litter (

). If we look at parasitic plants not only through the prism of dependence and parasite–host interaction, we can easily see moderators of the entire ecosystem in them, particularly by enriching the environment with minerals. 

proposed, Dryads, rather than Robin Hood or Dracula, as a mythological analogy consistent with the role of a parasite in facilitating the growth of nearby plants.

            Orobanchaceae
is the largest and most widely distributed family of root-parasitic angiosperms, with 102 genera and over 2100 species (

). Despite relatively low biomass, many species in this family negatively affect hosts, particularly invasive species in crops. However, most occur in seminatural habitats, and some 
form large
populations affecting multiple hosts, communities, and other trophic levels. 

Orobanche

L. (incl. 

Phelipanche
Pomel

) is the most diverse and numerous holoparasitic genus in the 
Orobanchaceae
family, with over 200 described species (

). More than 70 natural products have been described from species in 

Orobanche

s.l.
; however, only ca. thirty species were subjected to phytochemical analysis (

; 

). Holoparasitic 
Orobanchaceae
are a rich source of metabolites belonging to the phenylethanoid glycosides (PhGs), which have been reported to exhibit multiple biological and medicinal effects (

). Owing to their unique properties, some holoparasitic species, such as 

Cistanche
Hoffmanns & Link

, are considered for cultivation in specific regions of 
China
due to their long-term use in traditional Chinese medicine (

; 

). Recently, the use of 

Orobanche

as food and medicine has been gaining increasing interest (

). However, the amount and bioactivity of the polyphenolic compounds found in these parasites are very diverse and depend on both the host plant and organs of the parasite and environmental factors such as altitude (

, 

). Recent studies have clearly shown that holoparasitic 
Orobanchaceae
, particularly 

Orobanche

s.l.
, can accumulate significant amounts of toxic metals (

; 

; 

). Parasitic plants are most often obtained for herbal medicine from natural or seminatural habitats that appear to be unpolluted; however, they can grow in mountain areas with a natural share of metal-rich soils, bedrock, or saline desert areas. In areas with soils that are naturally rich in toxic metals, the circulation of elements is often disturbed, and there is a shortage of water; however, deep-rooted hosts have access to the water table (

).

