In this study, 

O. laxissima

was characterized by a high accumulation capacity of micro- and macroelements, including heavy metals (particularly Zn, Ni, and Cd). This bioaccumulation depended on the examined organ of the parasite and the species of the host which it parasitizes. Higher elemental concentrations in the soil were correlated with increased uptake by plants. The profile of polyphenols in the host species was both qualitatively and quantitatively different from the profile of the compounds in the parasite. Increased accumulation of elements, including parasites, and the production of specific metabolites (in our case, PhGs) may have an enhanced protective effect against drought, pest, herbivore, and disease damage (

; 

; 

). Moreover, polyphenols of parasites that are correlated with Cu and Zn are antagonistic to polyphenols correlated with Fe, Pb, Cr, and Ni. Our research indicates that parasites respond to disturbances in the ecosystem and can provide valuable information about the dynamics of the host-parasite relationship as well as the health of the ecosystem in response to pollution. Further research is required to determine whether parasites can be used as indicators of ecosystem stress and metalliferous soils. Soil environmental contamination can also suppress the immune response of host plants, thereby leading to an increase in the intensity of infection by the parasite due to synergistic effects. Similarly, pollution might not directly affect mistletoe growth on trees but makes them more susceptible to mistletoe infection (Kołodziejek et al., 2012). Parasites can reduce the content of heavy metals in the host. Parasites may help to provide a better understanding of the biological availability of pollutants in ecosystems. Parasites can be considered a keystone species, as parasitism itself as well as the ability of parasites to accumulate and convert high amounts of organic and inorganic compounds (in our case, PhGs) via distinct biochemical pathways affects parasite–host relationships as well as the entire ecosystem. Some mutualistic effects have been observed on trophic interactions in abiotic environments and other organisms (

). Future investigation into these relationships is needed, such as holoparasite litter and its impact on soil microbes or higher trophic levels. 

O. laxissima

is the most common plant parasite in forest and scrub communities. It is the most expansive holoparasitic species in the Caucasus, with its individual populations having up to several thousand shoots. Hence, it can act as a moderator of trophic dependencies and the structure of communities, both during its flowering and active parasitizing process and after the decomposition of nutrient-rich litter, thus affecting the entire ecosystem. 

O. laxissima

also has high bioactive potential; however, before medical use, it must be tested for heavy metal content or specifically cultivated for human consumption owing to its strong accumulation properties. Such accumulation characteristics have also been shown in studies of other holoparasitic species. They may be related to the physiology of holoparasites.

